For Indigenous environmental and human rights defender Helena Gualinga (@helenagualinga), the climate crisis is literally in her backyard. ‚ÄúLast year, as the first wave of the pandemic was hitting Ecuador, my community faced floods of unprecedented magnitudes, destroying schools, bridges, crops and washing away people‚Äôs homes,‚Äù says Helena, 19, who is a member of the Kichwa community of the Sarayaku. ‚ÄúPeople were left without homes and secure food sources for months, and a year later we still have not recovered completely. This is a result of a combination of climate change and deforestation.‚Äù‚Å£
‚Å£
Environmental activism has always been a part of Helena‚Äôs life. ‚ÄúWhen I was very young, my community was threatened by oil companies and immediately the people of my community decided to resist,‚Äù she says. ‚ÄúSo it‚Äôs always been there because it‚Äôs about defending our lands, our waters, our home.‚Äù‚Å£
‚Å£
This #EarthDay, Helena is hopeful. ‚ÄúI feel so privileged how I grew up in the Amazon. Seeing the children today doing all things I used to do as a child, like running around the forest, climbing enormous trees, sometimes I think, why is this even possible? It‚Äôs possible because my people fought for it. And that gives me hope ‚Äî that work is giving happiness to those children, and I really want that to continue.‚Äù üåé‚Å£

Ever wonder how prom started? üï∫üéäüé∂
Comedian Lonnie Marts IIV (@lonnieiiv) breaks down the origin story. üòÇüòÇ

‚ÄúMy prom experience was pretty standard. I was a weirdo in a Hawaiian shirt running around, hyping everybody up. And I think I did a really good job ‚Äî like, I would want to hang out with me at prom again,‚Äù says Lonnie, who describes his comedy as quirky, optimistic and thoughtful.

‚ÄúI‚Äôm an optimist so I look at a lot of things like, ‚ÄòHow can we have the most fun with this? How can we make this something that everyone will enjoy and want to be a part of?‚Äô I do that with my content, my audience and my community too ‚Äî I love involving people and bringing everybody together to just have a great time.‚Äù

Putting his humor aside, Lonnie recognizes that many proms this year may still look or feel different from proms of years past, but he has advice on keeping a positive outlook. ‚ÄúIf you‚Äôre missing out on something, it‚Äôs OK to be sad about it. Cry about it ‚Äî but then pick your head up, get with some good people who know how to be imaginative and get excited about doing what you can do and make it the best darn time you‚Äôve ever had.‚Äù üíõ‚ù§Ô∏è

‚ÄúI think one of the most beautiful things that we can give to one another is our vulnerability.‚Äù üíï

Introducing Vancouver, Canada-based singer/songwriter Jessia (@jessiamusic) and her latest hit ‚ÄúI‚Äôm Not Pretty,‚Äù a song that started as a form of personal therapy for the musician and has since become a far-reaching anthem for self-acceptance and body positivity.
üé∂ üíñ üé∂

‚ÄúI feel like the lyrics have helped me,‚Äù says Jessia. ‚ÄúI am the most confident I‚Äôve ever been in my body and I love the person that I look at in the mirror every morning. I don't think I ever felt that way before ‚ÄòI‚Äôm Not Pretty.‚Äô I also feel like I‚Äôm just the messenger of this song, and this song is so much bigger than just me as an artist.‚Äù

In theme with #MentalHealthAwarenessMonth, the message of Jessia‚Äôs song aims to inspire people to let go of the need for validation from others and to love themselves fully and freely.

‚ÄúAin‚Äôt nobody got time for social comparisons,‚Äù says Jessia. ‚ÄúJust do you and just rock it. Do exactly what you want to do and honestly it‚Äôs going to work out so much better than trying to be someone else. Building that relationship with yourself where you‚Äôre 100% comfortable with who you are is a really, really beautiful thing.‚Äù

For more resources from mental health experts and creators, check out our Guide on the ways to combat social comparison. And to hear more from Jessia, check out our story now! ‚ú®‚ú®

‚ÄúMy freestyle riding represents who I am. It is an extension of my personality and I use it to improvise through the world,‚Äù says professional bike athlete Brad Simms (@brad_simms).‚Å£
‚Å£
Brad was introduced to BMX at age 11 by his uncle. ‚ÄúSince then I have been privileged enough to ride my bike in 100+ countries, learn multiple languages, broaden my global perspective and make friends all around the world. I could not have done it without the bike.‚Å£
‚Å£
Freedom of expression is my favorite part about riding BMX. The process of connecting dots that never existed is a feeling that never grows old. You are constantly having to reassess your thinking, because of the mental agility it demands.‚Å£
‚Å£
My technique and trick selection are different at this stage of my career. I search for places to do tricks people think are impossible or unique. Jumping over stuff and riding on walls are my favorite things to do now.‚Å£
‚Å£
The streets are the best for my style of riding as I‚Äôm not confined to one course like I might be in competitions. When I pedal around the city, I don‚Äôt know who or what I will run into. The unknown is what keeps me going back day after day. The streets are raw, gritty and unforgiving so you have to always be alert.‚Äù‚Å£
‚Å£
Video of @brad_simms by @drewpickles

Darci Adele Shepard-Mobbs (@darciadele) and Mia Knights (@miaxalexis) represent the idyllic nature of their long-term relationship through a magical lens inspired by the Renaissance, 19th century English paintings and the folklore of fairies and elves.‚Å£
‚Å£
‚ÄúWe like to think the world we have created to be shown by these photos is one of complete content, happiness and calm, since that‚Äôs how we feel around one another,‚Äù explain the 18-year-olds who live in Norfolk, England.‚Å£
‚Å£
‚ÄúWe want to convey to people that it‚Äôs OK to wish for things, and that nobody should ever tell you that you can‚Äôt have something. We both used to believe that we would never be able to find the kind of love we now share, and that we weren‚Äôt even allowed to want it.‚Å£
‚Å£
We want to inspire the people that see the fairy tale life we live in to believe that it‚Äôs not just a wish, and that we are real people with insecurities and imperfections who worked as individuals to believe that we are worthy of love, as is everyone in the LGBTQ+ community if they want it.‚Å£
‚Å£
The best thing about being together is the knowledge that whatever we experience as individuals in life, good or bad, exciting or scary, we are going to have a best friend there to experience it at the same time.‚Äù‚Å£
‚Å£
Photo by @darciadele and @miaxalexis

Kim Saira‚Äôs (@kimsaira) art serves as both a creative healing mechanism for her own mental health and as a tool to support the API community. ‚Å£
 ‚Å£
‚ÄúAll of my work revolves around Asian American advocacy, and for telling my story through my experiences, growing up as an Asian American immigrant,‚Äù says the Filipina American artist. ‚Å£
 ‚Å£
‚ÄúThe anti-Asian hate crimes are no doubt triggering and terrifying. It‚Äôs also brought so many different communities together in a time of collective healing. It‚Äôs given me hope and strength that through the power of advocacy and uniting, we will get through this together. ‚Å£
 ‚Å£
One huge way the API community has been misunderstood is that we are a monolith and that we are all the same, which is incredibly untrue. I want my community and the world to know that API influence consists of so many different people coming from different cultures and backgrounds, and we all have an important role to play for diverse API representation.‚Äù ‚Å£
 ‚Å£
This month, we‚Äôre celebrating #APIHeritageMonth by sharing creative voices from the community. #RethinkOurInfluence ‚Å£
 ‚Å£
Art by @kimsaira

‚ÄúMy status as a professional athlete doesn‚Äôt exclude me from racism, discrimination, sexism or homophobia. The minute I take that jersey off, I am a Black, bisexual woman in America and as Malcolm X once said, '‚ÄúThe most unprotected person in America is the Black woman.‚Äù ‚ÄîTasha Cloud (@t__cloud9)

The 2021 @wnba season got underway this week and for the @washmystics point guard it marked the first time she has laced up for a game in over a year. Tasha opted out of the 2020 season in order to pursue social justice reform and use her platform for something far bigger than her sport.

‚ÄúIt was the hardest decision for me thus far in my career,‚Äù says Tasha. ‚ÄúBut I understood that this moment in time was much bigger than myself and my career. I‚Äôve been given this God-given platform to be a voice for the voiceless. If I didn‚Äôt use my voice, I‚Äôd be doing a disservice to a lot of people that look like me. I wanted to be on the frontlines; not only in spaces that hard dialogues and decisions were being made, but in the community, at marches and at protests.‚Äù

Heading into the new season, Tasha is confident her work as an activist and athlete will be championed by her league both on and off the court. ‚ÄúThe WNBA is constantly pushing boundaries and progressing the needle forward. We are consistently at the forefront of every social issue.‚Äù

Becoming a hairdresser was a natural evolution for 21-year-old Yesfira Sidorenko (@yesfira). ‚ÄúIn ninth grade, I got interested in doing hair from watching online tutorials, and started practicing on my little sisters,‚Äù says Yesfira, who was born in Latvia and lives in Alaska. ‚ÄúAfter high school, I decided to go to cosmetology school, got a job as a hairdresser, and this is where I am today.‚Äù Braids were one of Yesfira‚Äôs earliest styles she worked to perfect, and she‚Äôs stuck with them through the years, adding in more complex twists, waves and updos for weddings and special occasions. ‚ÄúIf I were going to #prom today, I would wear my hair in a loose mermaid wave, with my hair tucked to one side with a clip.‚Äù
